  "prompt": "What are time zones?",
  "response": "Time zones are geographical regions that observe a uniform standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes. The Earth is divided into 24 standard time zones, each roughly 15 degrees of longitude wide, with each zone typically representing a one-hour difference from the neighboring zones.\n\nKey points about time zones:\n\n1. Purpose\n- Standardize time across different regions\n- Coordinate activities across different locations\n- Align local time with solar time\n\n2. Prime Meridian\n- The starting point is the Greenwich Meridian (0 degrees longitude) in London, UK\n- Known as Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) or Coordinated Universal Time (UTC)\n\n3. Time Zone Variations\n- Some countries use a single time zone\n- Others span multiple time zones\n- Some countries have non-standard time zones with 30-minute or 45-minute differences\n\n4. Calculation\n- Time zones east of the Prime Meridian are ahead (+ hours)\n- Time zones west of the Prime Meridian are behind (- hours)\n\n5. Daylight Saving Time\n- Some regions adjust their clocks forward or backward seasonally\n- Aims to make better use of daylight hours\n\nTime zones help ensure consistent timekeeping across different parts of the world.",
